ment, The Effects of Prejudice and Discrimination on Personality Development, was a gratifying illus- tration of the possibility that even in the social and psychological sciences what is called "pure" re- search can sometimes have some direct social policy and applied social change effects. The Dark
otherwise disturb the convenience of their more powerful benefactors. Antipoverty programs based on these social realities were doomed to failure be- cause they reflected a total lack of commitment to eliminate poverty, to share power with the power- less. Above all, they reflected the inability of the
